1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Qxd4 g6 7. e4 d6 8. Be3 Bg7 9. f3 O-O 10. Qd2 Be6 {White's best reaction against Be6 is to push f4-f5, preferably in one move. With this move order, White is already committed to f2-f3 and it doesn't make much sense to push the pawn again.} 11. Rc1 Qa5 12. Nd5 {It is important to play this move now, before Black plays Rfc8} Qxd2+ $6 (12... Qxa2 {My computer is convincing me that this move is working and Black has nothing to worry about, but the practice shows that Black's play is not easy at all.} 13. Nxe7+ Kh8 14. Bd4 {1-0 Carlsen,M (2832)-Guseinov,G (2645) chess.com Speed 3m+2spm 2017 Chess.com INT blitz (1.16)}) (12... Qd8 {Doesn't make sense right now, because the rook is passive on the f8-square.}) 13. Kxd2 Bxd5 ({It is not possible to play} 13... Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bd7 15. Rc7 $18) 14. cxd5 $1 {We achieve a very typical endgame. Usually, this kind of endgame are in White's favour. He has a bishop pair and some pressure on the queenside. The king is also feeling quite comfortable in the centre.} (14. exd5 {Doesn't make sense now. Because our bishops occupy the e-file and we can't put pressure on the e7-pawn very easily.}) 14... Rfc8 (14... e6 {is the other line of defence}) 15. Be2 {White's plan is the following: 1.Push the queenside pawns as far as he can. Usually to a5-b4. Fixing the queenside structure and the weakness on "b7" 2.Gaining space on the kingside, trying to create a second weakness. 3. Exchange one pair of rooks to avoid dynamics 4. Open the position and penetrate} a6 16. b4 Kf8 (16... b5 $2 {is a very common mistake. Now Black pawns are more vulnerable and we can attack them later on, by means of a2-a4.}) 17. a4 Nd7 18. a5 {Part 1 is over} Bb2 19. Rc2 Rxc2+ 20. Kxc2 Bg7 21. Kb3 Rc8 22. Bd2 $1 {Instructive move. Usually,, the bishop pair works better when a pair of rooks is on the board. So White doesn't want to exchange the rooks.} Bd4 23. g4 Kg7 24. g5 Rc7 25. Rd1 Kf8 26. f4 Bg7 27. Bg4 Ke8 28. Rf1 Bd4 29. h4 Bg7 30. h5 Bd4 31. Rh1 Bg7 32. Rh3 Kf8 33. h6 $1 {An example play by Polugaevsky. He decided that sooner or later he would manage to open the position via e4-e5 and then the h7-weakness would decide the game,.} Bd4 34. Rd3 Ba7 35. Bh3 Bg1 36. Bc3 Ke8 37. e5 {Finally White opens the position} Bh2 38. exd6 exd6 39. Re3+ Kd8 40. Re4 Bg1 41. Bxd7 {As we know. One of the biggest strengths of the bishop pair is that we can always exchange one.} 1-0

