1. Nf3 g6 2. e4 Bg7 3. d4 d6 4. c4 c5 5. Nc3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 {You can see that we reach Maroczy Bind with another weird opening moves.} 7. Be3 Nf6 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Bd7 10. Qd2 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. f3 Nd7 13. Be3 $1 {In this structure, White should keep the bishops because exchanging them helps Black to reach his desirable endgame (Good N against bad B)} a5 14. b3 Nc5 15. Rac1 Qb6 16. Nd5 (16. Rc2 {Is the main theoretical move.}) 16... Bxd5 17. cxd5 {Again we will see the symmetrical structure after cxd5.} Rfc8 18. Rfd1 Qb4 19. Rc2 Nd7 20. Rdc1 Rxc2 21. Rxc2 Qxd2 22. Bxd2 {We get the same situation as in the Polugaevsky game with the difference that we control the c-file and Black's pawn is on "a5"} Bd4+ 23. Kf1 Nc5 {Marian manages to close the c-file and to stop b3-b4, but now White can slowly improve his position. The a5-pawn stops b4, but is also a weakness; now the b5-square is quite weak.} 24. Bb5 Kg7 25. Ke2 h5 (25... f5 {active counterplay was needed here.} 26. exf5 gxf5 27. Rc4 Be5 28. g3 $16) 26. h4 e5 $6 {This move allows White to create more weaknesses in Black's camp.} (26... f5 {again this break was better}) 27. dxe6 $1 {White almost always takes on e6 if he has a chance.} Nxe6 28. Bc4 Bc5 29. Kd3 Nc7 30. a4 b6 31. Bc3+ Kf8 32. Bf6 Ne8 33. Bb2 Nc7 {Black keeps the queenside safe, but Khalifman opens a second front} 34. g4 $1 Ke7 (34... hxg4 35. fxg4 Ne6 36. Rh2 $18 {[%cal Rh4h5]}) (34... Ne6 $1 {was probably the better chance because White should give his bishop pair now.} 35. Bxe6 fxe6 36. gxh5 gxh5 37. Rg2 $16) 35. gxh5 gxh5 36. Rg2 $18 d5 {desperation} 37. Bxd5 Nxd5 38. exd5 Kd6 39. Rg5 Re8 40. Bc1 Re1 41. Bf4+ Kd7 42. Rf5 Rf1 43. Bg5 Ke8 44. Kc4 Rb1 45. Bh6 Be7 46. Rxh5 Rf1 47. Re5 Kd7 48. Rf5 1-0

