1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6 8. f3 Bg7 9. Be3 Be6 10. Rc1 O-O 11. Qd2 Qa5 12. Nd5 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Bxd5 14. cxd5 Rac8 {In the classical Polugaevsky game, we saw 15.Be2, but Hungasky handles the position differently.} (14... Rfc8 {leads to the same}) 15. Rxc8 Rxc8 16. g3 Ne8 ({we can see White's main idea after:} 16... Nd7 17. Bh3 Rc7 18. Rc1 Rxc1 19. Kxc1 Nc5 20. Kc2 {[%cal Rb2b4]} a5 21. b3 $11 {[%cal Rc2c3,Ra2a3,Rb3b4]}) 17. Bh3 Rc7 18. Rb1 {Not giving access to the c3-square, but also keeping the rooks on the board.} b6 19. Kd3 Kf8 20. a4 Nf6 21. b4 Ke8 22. Rb3 Nd7 23. f4 Kd8 24. a5 Rb7 25. a6 Rb8 26. Ra3 Nf6 27. Rc3 Nxd5 $2 {This loses on the spot} (27... Ne8 {[%csl Re3][%cal Rh3g4,Rh2h4,Re4e5] is the better defence. But White has numerous ways to improve the position.}) 28. exd5 Bxc3 29. Kxc3 Kc7 30. Bf1 e6 31. Bb5 exd5 32. Kd4 h5 33. h4 Rh8 34. Kxd5 Rh7 35. f5 gxf5 36. Bf4 Rg7 37. Bxd6+ Kc8 38. Be2 1-0

