{In this game we will see one very typical situation. Good Black knight against White's light-squared bishop.} 1. Nf3 g6 2. e4 c5 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6 8. Be2 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd3 a5 11. Bd4 a4 12. O-O Qa5 13. f4 Be6 14. f5 Bd7 15. Kh1 (15. c5 $1 {White should hurry. This typical break gives White an advantage.} dxc5 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qxd7 $16 {Black has some compensation, but not enough}) 15... Bc6 {Now Black coordinates his pieces.} 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. exd5 (17. cxd5 Nd7 $17) 17... Nd7 {and Black gets the desirable endgame. White can't avoid the bishops' exchange due to the weakness of the b2-pawn.} 18. Bxg7 (18. Be3 Bxb2 $15) 18... Kxg7 19. Rad1 Ne5 20. Qe3 f6 21. Rf4 g5 22. Re4 h6 23. h4 Rac8 24. Kh2 Qc5 25. Qg3 Qb4 (25... b5 26. cxb5 Qc2 $17) 26. b3 axb3 27. axb3 Ra8 28. Bh5 {There is no attack. Black's king is perfectly safe and White's queenside is falling apart.} Ra3 29. Re3 b5 30. cxb5 Rc8 31. Be2 Ra2 $2 (31... Rc2 $1) 32. Bc4 Rxc4 33. bxc4 Qxc4 34. Rxe5 $1 dxe5 35. hxg5 hxg5 36. b6 (36. d6 {was stronger and Black is close to salvation}) 36... Ra8 37. Qf2 Qb3 38. Rc1 Qxd5 39. Qe3 Ra2 40. Qg3 Ra4 41. Qe3 Rg4 42. Qf2 Rf4 43. Qe3 Re4 44. Qf2 Rb4 45. Qe3 Rb2 46. Qh3 Qe4 47. Rc7 Qf4+ 48. Qg3 Kf7 49. b7 e4 50. Kh3 Qxf5+ 51. Kh2 Qf4 52. Kh3 Qxg3+ 53. Kxg3 f5 54. Rc5 e6 55. Rc7+ Kf6 56. Rd7 Ke5 57. Rc7 f4+ 58. Kh3 e3 59. Kg4 Rxg2+ 60. Kf3 Rf2+ 61. Kg4 Rb2 62. Kf3 e2 63. Rc5+ Kf6 0-1

