{Ideal Position for Black - Play on the queenside In this position, Black reaches almost the maximum. The knight is better than the bishop and all Black's pieces are very active. The weakness on d6 doesn't really matter. Black's plan in such cases is to create weaknesses on the queenside. [#]} 27... a4 $1 {One of the most typical ideas in Black in Maroczy is to prepare the a5-a4 break which at the moment when White can't answer it with b3-b4.} 28. bxa4 {sad necessity. Otherwise White loses a pawn.} Qxa4 29. Rd2 Qb4 30. Rb2 Qc3 31. Qd2 Qf6 $1 {a general rule in such positions is that the side with the knight should try to keep the queens on the board.} 32. Rb1 h5 $1 {Another typical idea. Black starts winning space on the queenside, eventually creating a weakness.} 33. Re1 Rxe1 34. Qxe1 Qe5 35. Qf2 (35. Qxe5 dxe5 {The endgame is hopeless for White. Black is playing practically with a pawn up and the knight is much stronger than the bishop.}) 35... Kf8 36. g3 h4 37. gxh4 {This makes White's king weak. The engines like this move, but practically I think it is a mistake.} (37. Kg2 {looks more natural}) 37... Ne6 38. Qd2 Nd4 39. Kg2 Nf5 40. Qf2 Qf4 41. Kh3 (41. h5 $5 {was the only way to stay in the game. Although Black keeps the advantage after:} gxh5) 41... Nxh4 {This is probably what White missed} 42. Qg3 Qf6 43. f4 Nf5 44. Qe1 Qd4 45. Kg2 {Here Tukmakov just resigned} 0-1

