1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 d6 {An important position to understand. Black still didn't show where he will develop the bishop (e6 or d7-c6), so White also keeps his pawn still on f2. White is ready to met Be6 with f2-f4 and against Bd7-c6 he can play f3.} 9. O-O (9. Qd2 {is another possibility. Remember that Ng4 is never a threat. White is not afraid of this trade.} Ng4 10. Bxg4 {White is more than happy to exchange his potentially bad bishop for Black's knight.} Bxg4 11. O-O) 9... Ng4 $4 {This horrible mistake was played in 174 games in my database. Once a GM played it against me in a tournament blitz game.} ({Black has two decent plans in this position} 9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6) (9... Bd7 10. Qd2 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6) 10. Bxg4 Bxg4 11. Nxc6 Bxd1 12. Nxd8 $18 {and White is simply with a piece up.} *

