{[%evp 0,83,19,38,40,41,106,109,89,80,75,33,26,23,41,58,42,19,23,14,3,3,13,27,18,-6,-18,-52,-69,-39,-39,-55,-63,-72,-46,-69,13,3,0,0,0,5,0,0,0,0,10,6,6,-6,55,60,56,64,99,76,148,142,149,153,152,154,151,152,151,160,161,161,162,166,226,228,232,229,224,234,264,254,257,260,271,263,269,201,203,199] In the following examples we will see some important ideas for Black in Maroczy Bind Black plays Qb6} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6 8. Be2 Bg7 9. Bg5 O-O 10. O-O Be6 11. Qe3 Qb6 $5 {Black allows double pawns and worse pawn structure but gets two semi-open files in return and some temporary activity. You should remember that in general White is always doing very well in Maroczy if the position is calm. Black is the one who is trying to go for complication and seek dynamic play.} 12. Qxb6 $5 {[%mdl 4] Recently, this move gains some popularity} (12. Qd2 {Is also possible, but it is also a concession. White is losing some time.}) 12... axb6 13. Bd2 $146 {[%mdl 8] This move looks consolidating, but Black should have enough counterplay.} (13. Rac1 {is possible too, but leaves the a2-pawn unprotected which gives Black very decent counterplay in different ways.} b5 $1 {Another very typical and dynamic break. The c3-knight needs to protect the e4-pawn.} (13... h6 $5 14. Be3 Nd7 $15 {[%cal Rf8c8,Rg7c3,Ra8a2]}) 14. cxb5 Bxa2 15. e5 {Interesting pawn sacrifice for activating the e2-bishop} (15. Be3 $11) 15... dxe5 16. Bf3 e4 17. Nxe4 Nd5 (17... Nxe4 {should equalize easily} 18. Bxe4 Ra5 $11) 18. Nc5 b6 (18... Rfc8 {keeps the balance, but you should agree that in a blitz game Black's move looks more natural} 19. Nxb7 Bxb2) 19. Nd7 Rfe8 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Nxb6 {White won a pawn and later the game in: 1-0 (59) Hansen,E (2606)-Mekhitarian,K (2569) Chess.com INT 2022}) 13... Rfc8 14. b3 Nd7 15. Rfc1 Nc5 16. f3 b5 (16... Ra3 $1 {[%cal Rc8a8] looks very strong}) 17. cxb5 Nxb3 {Objectively speaking this move is still ok, but White's play is much easier after it.} ({The immediate:} 17... Bxb3 {doesnt work due to:} 18. axb3 Rxa1 19. Rxa1 Nxb3 20. Nd5 $3 {[%csl Re7][%cal Rd5e7] and White is holding}) (17... Kf8 $3 {is a great preparation move to protect the e7-pawn. Now there is almost no defence against Bxb3. For example} 18. Kf1 Bxb3 19. axb3 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 Nxb3 21. Ra2 Nxd2+ 22. Rxd2 Rxc3 {With very good chances for Black to convert his advantage}) 18. axb3 Rxa1 19. Rxa1 Bxc3 20. Bxc3 Rxc3 21. Ra7 Rxb3 22. Rxb7 Kf8 23. Rb8+ Kg7 24. b6 Rb1+ (24... Rb2 {not allowing White to activate his king.} 25. b7 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Rd7c6]}) 25. Kf2 Rb2 26. Ke3 d5 27. Bd3 dxe4 28. Bxe4 $18 f5 29. Bc6 Rc2 30. b7 Rxc6 31. Rd8 Rb6 32. b8=Q Rxb8 33. Rxb8 Kf6 34. Rb6 g5 35. Kd4 f4 36. Ke4 Kf7 37. Ke5 Bc8 38. h4 gxh4 39. Kxf4 h3 40. g4 h5 41. Rh6 hxg4 42. fxg4 1-0

