1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 ({White can't punish Black for delaying Bg7} 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5 $2 Qa5+ $17 {[%cal Ba5e5]}) 6... d6 {This is a tricky move order} 7. Be2 (7. Be3 $6 {Is another mistake} Ng4 8. Nxc6 (8. Bc1 $2 Qb6 $19) 8... bxc6 9. Bd4 (9. Bc1 Bg7 $15) 9... e5) 7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Bg5 {Sometimes White develops the bishop on g5. The idea is to put some pressure on the e7-pawn and sometimes to have the idea Bxf6} O-O 10. Qd2 {White is forced to spend a tempo removing the queen} Be6 (10... a5 {is still possible}) 11. Rc1 {The move order is important. White usually starts with this move to avoid problems on the a1-h8 diagonal.} (11. O-O {actually this move is possible} Rc8 12. b3 b5 13. cxb5 (13. e5 $1 dxe5 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Nxb5 $16) 13... Rxc3 14. Qxc3 Nxe4 $11) 11... a6 12. f3 {[%csl Bc4]} (12. b3 {is better and stops b5}) 12... Rc8 (12... b5 {this strike also works very well here}) 13. b3 b5 {now the position becomes very concrete} 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Nxb5 (15. Bxb5 Rxc3 16. Rxc3 Qa5 17. O-O (17. Be2 Nxe4 $19 {[%cal Rg7c3]}) 17... Nxe4 $19) (15. Kf2 b4 16. Nb5 Qa5 $132 (16... Qb6+ 17. Be3 Bh6 $1 $11)) 15... Rxc1+ 16. Qxc1 Qa5+ 17. Qd2 Ra8 18. Nc3 (18. Qxa5 {White should already think about equalizing and agree to an equal position after:} Rxa5 19. a3 Bxb3 $11 {[%cal Bb3a4]}) 18... h6 19. Be3 {[%cal Be1g1]} Ng4 $1 20. Bd4 Bxd4 21. Qxd4 Rc8 22. Kd2 (22. fxg4 Rxc3 23. O-O Rc2 $17) 22... Qg5+ $2 (22... Ne5 {[%cal Re5c6,Rc6b4] and Black has a fantastic compensation for the sacrificing pawn.}) 23. Kc2 Ne3+ $2 24. Kb2 Qxg2 25. Qxe3 $4 (25. Re1 $18) 25... Qxh1 $19 26. Qxh6 Qe1 27. Bc4 Qf2+ 28. Ka1 Qd4 29. Qc1 Bxc4 30. bxc4 Qxc4 31. Kb2 Qb4+ {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

