{In this game we will see the very interesting idea for Black - Bxc3} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Bd7 10. Nc2 {Interesting idea, which we already saw in the Carlsen-Le game. White is avoiding the exchange of the knights.} Be6 {Not the most popular move, but a very logical one. If Black is allowed to lose a tempo, Black can do the same. The typical idea here is to transfer the knight to c5.} 11. f3 Nd7 12. Qd2 Qa5 {Itturizaga has this position three times in his practice.} 13. Rab1 (13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Rfc8 15. b3 a6 (15... Bxd4+ 16. Qxd4 Qc5 $11) 16. Rfc1 Bxd4+ 17. Qxd4 Rc7 $11 {0-1 Egoroff,J (2311)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2656) Latin Cup Montevideo 2011 (4)}) 13... Bxc3 {very typical exchange in the Nc2 system. Black is giving his strongest piece, but creates weaknesses on the queenside and ruins White's structure. Also White doesn't have some of the most typical ideas (b2-b4 and Nd5 jump). The obvious drawback is that Black's king is weakened now, but usually, Black plays f7-f6 and it is not easy for White to do anything on the kingside.} 14. bxc3 Nde5 15. Bh6 Nxc4 16. Qd1 (16. Bxc4 Bxc4 17. Bxf8 Bxf1 18. Bxe7 {is very close to equal}) 16... Rfc8 17. Nd4 Nd8 $15 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Kh1 Qh5 20. Bc1 Qc5 21. f4 Ne3 22. Bxe3 Qxe3 23. f5 Rxc3 {Black bravely takes material. It seems that White doesn't have enough resources to create an attack.} 24. fxg6 hxg6 25. e5 d5 26. Bh5 Qg5 27. Bxg6 Rac8 (27... Qxg6 {is stronger and ends the game immediately} 28. Rb4 {probably Black was afraid of this move} Nf7 29. Rg4 Ng5 30. h4 Rc4 $19) 28. Be8 (28. Bd3 Nf7 29. Qe2 {White is still in the game}) 28... R8c4 29. h3 a6 30. Qe2 Rc2 31. Qf3 Rf4 {Very nice game by Iturrizaga which shows the strength of the Bxc3 idea.} 0-1

