{[%evp 0,75,16,28,46,51,56,42,41,51,103,32,24,33,52,39,42,10,1,-4,51,-11,-3,0,24,37,51,39,74,61,69,70,70,59,68,58,73,77,64,66,85,76,82,82,94,90,92,86,123,150,143,113,196,186,186,215,183,208,211,91,304,276,276,322,322,210,248,293,333,491,598,915,906,925,987,862,1045,960]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6 8. Be3 Bg7 9. f3 Be6 10. Rc1 O-O 11. Qd2 Qa5 12. b3 a6 13. Nd5 Qd8 {GM Tiviakov is a big specialist in Maroczy for Black. He decided to keep the queens on the board.} 14. Bb6 Qd7 15. Be2 Bxd5 16. cxd5 ({After:} 16. exd5 e6 {is very strong} 17. dxe6 Qxe6 {Black has enough dynamic resources to keep the balance due to the undefended b6-bishop.} 18. O-O d5 $11) 16... Rfc8 17. O-O Qe8 18. Be3 Nd7 19. g3 Nc5 (19... Rxc1 20. Rxc1 Rc8 21. Kg2 h5 22. Rc2 Qd8 23. Rxc8 Qxc8 24. Qc1 {White keeps the pressure even without the major pieces on the board.}) 20. Rc2 $1 {[%cal Rf1c1]} a5 {Black is trying to stop b4, but this move weakens the b5-square and White sooner or later will succeed with the b4-break.} 21. Rfc1 b6 22. Qd1 $1 {preparing a3-b4} Qf8 23. a3 Rcb8 (23... Bh6 {is not working, because White wins a piece after:} 24. Bxh6 Qxh6 25. b4 $18) 24. b4 axb4 25. axb4 Nb3 $2 {This is an understandable mistake. Black is trying to get some counterplay. Unfortunately for him, White has everything under control and there are no tricks.} (25... Nd7 {is the only way to stay in the game, but White has a very easy play after:} 26. Bb5 Nf6 27. Qd3 Bh6 28. f4 $18) 26. Rb1 Ra3 27. Rc6 $18 {The game is practically over} Na1 28. Bxb6 f5 29. Bd4 Rba8 30. e5 Bxe5 31. Bxe5 dxe5 32. b5 e4 33. b6 exf3 34. Bxf3 Qh6 35. b7 Qe3+ 36. Kh1 Kf7 37. bxa8=Q Rxa8 38. d6 1-0

