{White Attacks on the Kingside - Rook Lift} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Bd7 10. Qd2 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. Bd3 {[%cal Ra1e1,Re1e3] This system is quite dangerous for Black. White protects the pawn with the bishop and is ready quickly to go for the f4-f5 idea. Also the bishop is freeing the e-file for the Re1-e3 lift.} a5 13. Rae1 (13. Rfe1 {Some players prefer this move based on some little nuances, but it is out of the scope of our lecture. In my opinion the rook is more useful on f1}) 13... Nd7 (13... a4 {I like this tricky move. Black is preparing Qa5 and avoiding the trades of the bishops.} 14. f4 {doesn't give much for White after:} (14. Nd5 Nd7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Re3 e5 17. Rh3 h5 {seems risky, but Black is doing OK in this line.}) 14... e5 $1 15. fxe5 Ng4 {With a good counterplay for Black}) 14. Bxg7 {In this line, White exchanges the bishop. Strategically speaking Black is doing fine, but White has a straightforward plan and in practice it is not easy to defend this position for Black.} Kxg7 15. Re3 Qb6 (15... h6 {is a nice defending move. I am not sure that it equalizes completely, but at least the game is not so sharp after it.} 16. Rh3 Rh8 17. f4 Qb6+ 18. Kh1 Qc5 19. Rg3 Rag8 {[%cal Rg7f8] The line of defense is quite interesting. Although the engine is not so happy about Black's position. I think that from a human point of view, Black is doing OK.}) (15... e5 {is a pawn sacrifice} 16. Be2 Nc5 (16... Nf6 {Is another idea, which also didn't equalize} 17. Rd1 Qb6 18. Qxd6 Qxb2 {was played in practice, but Black is hopeless after:} (18... Rad8 $1 {Is the better try} 19. Qxe5 Rfe8 20. Qf4 Rxd1+ 21. Nxd1 Nxe4 22. h4 $16) 19. Qxe5 $18) 17. Rd1 Ne6 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 Nd4 $44 {0-1 Kleinman,M (2394)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2650) PRO League Stage Chess.com INT rapid 2018 (1) Looks quite nice for Black. Again the engine does not agree with me, but I quite like it for Black from a practical point}) 16. Rh3 h5 (16... Nf6 {was given in some old sources, but} 17. Qh6+ Kg8 18. g4 {[%cal Rd3e2,Rg4g5] looks winning for White}) (16... Rh8 {is the best defence, but White can choose between two equally good continuations} 17. Qh6+ (17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 h5 19. Re1 $14) 17... Kg8 18. Be2) 17. Rxh5 gxh5 18. Qg5+ Kh8 19. Qxh5+ Kg7 20. Qg5+ Kh8 21. Re1 (21. e5 {looks winning, but it seems that Black can hold after:} f5 $3 $11) 21... Ne5 (21... Qd4 $3 {Black has this incredible resource} 22. Re3 (22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. Re3 Ne5 24. Ne2 Ng4 25. Qh4 Qg7 26. Rg3 Bd7 $11) 22... Qg7 23. Rh3+ Kg8 24. Qe3 Ne5 $11) 22. Re3 $18 Qxe3 23. Qxe3 Nxd3 24. Qxd3 Rg8 25. Nd5 Bxd5 26. Qxd5 {White is already winning} Kg7 27. Qxb7 Rgb8 28. Qd5 a4 29. h4 f6 30. h5 Ra7 31. Qf5 Rab7 32. Qg6+ Kh8 33. Qf7 Rxb2 34. Qxe7 Rxa2 35. Qxf6+ Kg8 36. h6 Rb7 37. c5 Rc2 38. cxd6 a3 39. Qg6+ Kf8 40. h7 Rxh7 41. Qxh7 a2 42. Qh8+ Kf7 43. d7 1-0

