{The Plan with Na4} 1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. e4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6 8. Be3 Bg7 9. f3 O-O 10. Qd2 Qa5 11. Rc1 (11. Be2) 11... Be6 {We get to one of the most important positions in The Maroczy. White already plays f3, so Black chooses to develop the bishop to e6.} 12. Be2 Rfc8 13. b3 {We should note that this move is just impossible with the rook on a1.} a6 14. Na4 {White is using the drawback of Black's last move} (14. Nd5 $5 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nxd5 16. cxd5 Bd7 {White still keeps a tiny advantage, but Black should be able to hold.}) (14. O-O b5 $1 15. Nd5 {is pretty much forced} Qxd2 16. Bxd2 Nxd5 17. cxd5 Bd4+ 18. Kh1 Bd7 $11) 14... Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nd7 16. g4 $1 {This is a good prophylactic move. White is preparing to meet f5} (16. Rc2 f5 {and Black takes the initiative} 17. Bd3 Rc6 {with decent counterplay}) 16... f5 ({After the passive:} 16... Rc6 {[%cal Rh2h4,Rh4h5] White has different ways to improve the position.}) 17. exf5 ({After:} 17. gxf5 gxf5 18. Rhg1 Kh8 19. Bd3 {Black continues} f4 $1 20. Bf2 (20. Bxf4 Rf8 {Is pretty good for Black}) 20... Bf6 {[%cal Rc8g8] Preparing Rg8 and Ne5. Black's position looks pretty solid}) 17... gxf5 18. h3 {This is the trendy way to handle the position. White keeps the tension on the kingside.} Rf8 19. f4 {Black's main problem in this line is that it is very hard to find counterplay. White simply improves his position slowly.} Rad8 20. g5 Bf7 21. Rhd1 e5 22. Ke1 exf4 {[%csl Rd6,Rf5]} 23. Bxf4 {now both d6 and f5-pawns are quite weak.} Be5 24. Bxe5 Nxe5 {[%cal Rf7e6,Rf5f4] Black hopes with an active counterplay to compensate for the worse structure.} (24... dxe5 25. Rd6 {[%cal Rc1d1] with a total domination.}) 25. Nc3 Be6 26. Kf2 Kg7 27. Rd4 f4 28. Bf1 Nf7 {Guseinov went for counterplay based on the weakness of the g5-pawn.} (28... Nc6 {is the engine's way to handle the position. Although I think that White is still better after:} 29. Rd2 Kg6 30. Rcd1) 29. Re1 $1 {White sacrifices a pawn, but takes the initiative.} Nxg5 (29... Bc8) 30. h4 Nh3+ 31. Bxh3 Bxh3 32. Ne4 {now it is obvious that Black can't keep his material advantage.} h5 33. Ng5 $6 (33. Nxd6 $1 Rd7 34. c5 $16 {[%cal Re1e4,Rb3b4,Ra2a4,Rb3b5]}) 33... Bg4 34. Re7+ Kg6 35. Rxb7 Rde8 36. Ne4 (36. Nh7) 36... Re6 $11 37. Rb6 Rfe8 38. Nc3 Kf5 (38... Re3 39. Rbxd6+ Kf5 $11) 39. Rd5+ Re5 40. Rbxd6 Rxd5 41. Rxd5+ Kf6 42. Rd4 $18 Kf5 43. b4 Bf3 44. a4 Re3 45. Nd5 Bxd5 46. cxd5 1-0

