1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 c5 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Nc2 {This move makes a lot of sense. White has space advantage and not allows the exchange the d4-knight. The drawback of this move is that White loses time and moves the knight from the centre.} O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. Be3 Nd7 10. Qd2 a5 11. O-O Nc5 {Black follows his main plan in Maroczy: to transfer the knight to the c5-square.} 12. f3 a4 {freeing the a5-square for the queen and winning more space on the queenside.} 13. Rab1 Qa5 14. Kh1 Be6 15. Rfc1 Rfc8 16. Na3 {The knight looks ugly here, but it actually stays pretty well. White stops any a4-a3 ideas and the knight protects c4-pawn and can jump to b5 at an appropriate moment. Both sides finishes the development. Black will try to put some pressure on the queenside, while White will calmly maneuvers and improve his position. Black's main problem is that he did almost everything that he can. It is hard to imagine better squares for his pieces; still, there are no real threats.} h5 {This move is typical for Maroczy, but sometimes just weakened Black's structure.} 17. Bf1 Ne5 18. Qd1 {Carlsen is preparing Nd5, but he wants to keep the queens on the board.} Kh7 19. Bd2 Qd8 20. Be3 Qa5 21. Nd5 {Finally White starts active actions} Bxd5 {Of course, it is hard to tolerate such knight} 22. exd5 $1 {Great move, leaves Black without any counterplay.} Ned7 23. Nb5 Qd8 24. Rc2 Be5 25. f4 Bg7 26. f5 {Carlsen doesn't even care about the e5-square. He just starts an attack against Black's king} Ne5 27. Be2 Qd7 28. Nd4 gxf5 29. Bxh5 {Black is probably wondering why he plays h7-h5 few moves ago.} Ng6 30. Qf3 e6 31. dxe6 fxe6 32. Qh3 Qe7 33. Rf1 {One good thing about the space advantage is that you can easily switch from one flang to another} Rh8 34. Nxf5 {The final blow} exf5 35. Bxg6+ Kg8 36. Qxf5 Be5 37. Bf7+ Kf8 38. Bd5+ Ke8 39. Qg6+ Kd7 40. Rf7 Raf8 {An absolute masterpiece by the World Champion} 1-0

