{The structure after cxd5. Typical endgame} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bg7 5. e4 Nc6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Ng4 {This was a popular continuation, but nowadays it has a dubious reputation.} 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 Ne6 (9... e5 {is possible too, but White is better after:} 10. Bd3) 10. Qd2 Qa5 11. Rc1 d6 (11... g5 {[%cal Rb7b6,Rc8b7] Sometimes Black chooses this way of handling the position. Trying to keep the dark squares under control. White should react pretty calmly to this.} 12. Be2 b6 13. O-O Bb7 14. f3 {[%cal Rf1f2] Followed by Rf2-Bf1, keeping everything under control and not giving Black any dynamic changes.}) 12. Be2 Nc5 13. f3 Be6 14. b3 O-O 15. Nd5 {So When Black can't take with the knight on d5, this jump is always an idea. Now Andreikin forces Black to enter an unpleasant endgame.} Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Bxd5 17. cxd5 {White has two threats: 1.Bxc5 2.b3-b4 Black can't stop both and decides to sacrifice a pawn.} a5 18. Bxc5 dxc5 19. Rxc5 Rfc8 20. Rc4 e6 21. dxe6 fxe6 22. Rd1 Kf8 23. Ke3 $18 {White manages to convert his material advantage} Ke7 24. f4 Rxc4 25. Bxc4 e5 26. f5 Rd8 27. Bd5 b5 28. g4 Bh6+ 29. Kd3 gxf5 30. gxf5 Rc8 31. a3 b4 32. axb4 axb4 33. Ra1 Rc3+ 34. Ke2 Rc2+ 35. Kf3 Rxh2 36. Ra6 Rh4 37. Kg3 Bg5 38. f6+ Kd7 39. Be6+ Kc7 40. f7 1-0

