{In this game we will analyze one of the main tabyas in the Maroczy Bind. I will present you briefly the variation with 15...e6. According to theory White is slightly better, but I like the dynamic potential of Black's position.} 1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. e4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Bd7 10. Qd2 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. f3 a5 13. b3 Nd7 14. Be3 (14. Bxg7 Kxg7 {[%csl Bd7,Be2] This exchange helps Black to reach the desired endgame with a strong knight against a bad bishop. In most occasions, White sooner or later plays Nd5 and after the exchange Bxd5 we reach the piece configuration that Black wants.} 15. Rab1 (15. Qd4+ Kg8 {[%cal Yd8b6] followed by Qb6 which gives Black a very good play.}) 15... Qb6+ 16. Kh1 Nc5 {[%cal Bb6b4,Ba5a4,Bf8c8]} 17. a3 $6 {runs to} ({The immediate} 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 Qb4 {looks pretty good for Black. The typical a5-a4 break is coming.}) 17... Nxb3 $1 18. Qb2 a4 19. Nd5+ Qd4 20. Nxe7 Rfe8 21. Nxc6 bxc6 22. Rfd1 Qxb2 23. Rxb2 Rad8 {[%cal Bh7g7,Bg7f6,Bf6e6,Bb3c5] with an advantage for Black 0-1 (39) Bologan-Iturrizaga Berlin blitz 2015.}) 14... Nc5 15. Rab1 {[%cal Bf1c1] This is the main move in this position. White is leaving the c1-square for the other rook. His idea is slowly to prepare the advance a3-b4} e6 $5 {[%cal Bd8e7,Bd8h4] I like this move a lot because it gives Black a lot of dynamic chanцes. The idea is to cover the d5-square and to prepare Qh4 in many lines. The obvious drawback is that now the d6-pawn is very weak, but Black compensates this with active play. White has numerous ways to meet Black's idea.} ({The main line was always the move:} 15... Qb6 16. Rfc1 Qb4 $6 (16... Rfc8 17. Rc2 Qd8) (16... Qd8 $1 {[%cal Rb7b6,Rc5d7] This is better, but White's play still looks easier}) 17. Rc2 $1 {protecting the queen and preparing the maneuver Qd2-c1} Rfc8 18. Qc1 Qb6 19. a3 $16) 16. Rfd1 (16. Rfc1 {White is freeing the f1-square for the bishop and overprotects the c3-knight.} Be5 $1 17. Bf1 (17. Qe1 {is very well met by} f5 $1 18. exf5 Rxf5 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Yc6h1]} 19. Nd1 Qf6 20. Bf2 Rf8 {.} 21. Ne3 Rg5 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Yc6f3] with a lot of pressure against White's king. Soon the tactics will come.} 22. Kh1 Ne4 $1 23. fxe4 (23. Bg1 {can be met by} Ng3+ $1 24. hxg3 Rh5+ 25. Bh2 Rxh2+ $1 26. Kxh2 (26. Kg1 Qg5 $1) 26... Qh4+ 27. Kg1 Bxg3 $19) 23... Qxf2 24. Qxf2 Rxf2 $19 {0-1 (50) Erwich,F (2370)-Van der Lende,I (2331) Haarlem 2015}) (17. Kh1 $2 Qh4 $1 18. f4 (18. Bg1 Bf4 $1) (18. h3 Qg3 19. Bg1 Bf4 $15) 18... Bxc3 19. Qxc3 Nxe4 $17 {Kultiyasov-Guseinov, Minsk rapid 2015}) 17... Qe7 (17... Qh4 $5 18. g3 Qh5 19. Bg2 f5) (17... f5 $5 18. exf5 Rxf5 19. f4 Bg7 20. g3 e5 $13) 18. Rc2 $6 {A little slow.} f5 $1 {[%cal Bf5f4]} 19. exf5 Rxf5 $1 {0-1 Kveinys,A (2527)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2653) Riga Tech op 4th 2014 (9)}) (16. Bd1 $5 {[%cal Bd1c2,Bd2h2] This is another typical idea to remember. White is transferring the bishop to the c2-square from where it protects the e4-pawn. Also now the queen defends the second rank. The drawback is that Black now wastes a lot of time.} Be5 17. Bc2 Qe7 18. a3 Rfd8 (18... Rfc8 $5 {[%csl Gc8] is a possible improvement of Black's play}) 19. Rfd1 Qh4 20. h3 (20. g3 $2 Qf6 $17 {[%csl Rc3,Rf3]}) 20... Qe7 {White is probably better, but Black still has a lot of potential ½- (51) ½ (51) Bachmann,A (2614) -Felgaer,R (2580) Asuncion 2015}) (16. a3 {This move doesn't work very well now. Black has the following typical counterattacking idea.} a4 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Gc5][%cal Yc5b3,Yd8f6,Yg7c3]} 17. b4 Nb3 18. Qd3 Qf6 $1 {[%csl Rc3] White can't protect the knight by means of Rc1 and the d5-square is not available.} 19. Na2 {[%csl Ra2]} (19. Nd1 Rfd8 $1 20. f4 (20. b5 Be8 21. Bb6 Rd7 $15 {[%cal Yd6d5,Yb3c5]}) 20... d5 21. cxd5 exd5 22. e5 Qe6 $15 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Yd5d4,Yf7f6] and Black is on top.}) 19... d5 $1 20. cxd5 (20. b5 d4 $1 21. bxc6 dxe3 22. cxb7 Rab8 23. Qxe3 Rxb7 $15 {[%csl Ra3,Gg7][%cal Yf6e7]}) 20... exd5 21. b5 Bd7 {0-1 (38) Abdulla,K (2226) -Morchiashvili,B (2377) Nakhchivan 2013}) (16. Nd1 {[%cal Yd1f2] This maneuver seems too artificial for me. Black can simply continue with f5.} f5 17. exf5 gxf5 $1) 16... Be5 {[%csl Gc3,Ge4,Bd8][%cal Bd8h4]} 17. Nb5 $2 (17. Bd4 Qe7 18. Bf1 (18. Bxe5 dxe5 19. Qd6 Qxd6 20. Rxd6 f5) (18. a3 a4 $1 19. Bxe5 dxe5 20. b4 Nb3 21. Qe3 (21. Qd6 $2 Qg5 $1 $15) 21... Nd4) 18... Rfd8 (18... Rad8 $5 {[%csl Gf8][%cal Yf7f5]} 19. Qe3 (19. Bxe5 dxe5 20. Qe3 f5) 19... Bxd4 20. Rxd4 e5 21. Rd2 {[%csl Gf8][%cal Bc5e6,Be6d4]} f5 {0-1 (55) Bok-Lie, Wijk aan Zee 2010.}) 19. Qe3 Bxd4 20. Rxd4 e5 21. Rd2 Ne6 22. Rbd1 $14 {[%cal Yg2g3,Yh2h4,Yf1h3] 1-0 (59) Topalov,V (2700)-Reinderman,D (2542) Wijk aan Zee 1999}) (17. Qe1 Qf6 18. Rbc1 Rfd8 (18... Rad8 {and after} 19. Bf1 Bf4 (19... g5 $5) 20. Bxf4 Qxf4) 19. Bf1 g5 $1 {[%csl Re4,Rf3,Rg2,Gg5][%cal Yg5g4,Yf6c3,Ye5f4] 0-1 (40) Kuzubov,Y (2661)-Guseinov,G (2592) Doha 2014}) (17. g3 Qe7 18. Rbc1 Rad8 {[%cal Yf7f5] ½- (27) ½ (27) Rodshtein,M (2689)-Mista,A (2593) Drancy 2016}) (17. Bf1 $2 Qh4 $1 18. g3 (18. f4 Bxc3 19. Qxc3 Nxe4 $15 {(27)-1/2 Nemeth-Tate, A Heviz 2012.}) (18. h3 Qg3 $1 19. f4 Bxc3 20. Qxc3 Nxe4 {0-1 (25) Barreto Filho-El Debs, Santos 2012.}) 18... Qf6 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Ge5,Rf3,Gf6][%cal Yf6c3,Yf6f3] ½- (34) ½ (34) Kryvoruchko,Y (2707)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2653) Dubai 2014}) 17... Qh4 $1 18. g3 (18. h3 Qg3 $1 $19) 18... Bxg3 $1 19. hxg3 Qxg3+ 20. Kf1 (20. Kh1 Nxe4 $1 21. Qd3 {was seen in Nielsen, P-Larsen,B Esbjerg 1997,} (21. fxe4 Bxe4+ 22. Bf3 Bxf3+ $19) 21... Nf6 $1 $19 {[%cal Yf6g4]}) 20... Nxe4 $1 21. Qb2 f5 22. Nd4 Bd7 23. Rd3 e5 24. Nb5 f4 {0-1 (24) Bogdanovich,S (2590)-Guseinov,G (2634) Berlin 2015} *

