{In the following examples we will check the theoretical reccomendations in the most popular lines in Maroczy} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Bg7 6. Nc2 {The idea of this knight withdrawal is to avoid simplifications.} (6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 d6 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Bd7 10. Nb3 $5 {[%csl Rd7] Played with the same idea as 6.Nc2, but here the knight is not well positioned and its coordination is poor.} a5 $1 {[%csl Rb3] Immediately punishing the previous move.} 11. Rc1 a4 12. Nd2 a3 $1 {[%csl Gb4]} 13. b3 Nb4 $132 {[%csl Gb4,Rd2][%cal Gb4a2,Gb4c2,Gb4d3] Black becomes the owner of important squares on the queenside.} 14. f3 Bc6 15. Ndb1 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gc3d5]} Nd7 16. Kh1 Qa5 17. Bd2 Qb6 18. Qe1 e6 {[%csl Rb1] The poor performance of the knight on b1 is appreciated.} 19. Na4 Rxa4 $1 20. bxa4 Nxa2 {[%csl Ga3]} 21. Rd1 Bxa4 $17 {0-1 (31) Pelletier,Y (2593)-Bologan,V  (2671)/Aix les Bains 2011}) 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Nd7 10. Bd2 $1 {Giving extra protection to the square c3.} (10. Be3 $6 {This is an imprecision, as it allows the exchange of the black bishop on g7 for the knight on c3, ruining the white pawn structure. We arrive at a strategically complex situation.} Nc5 (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 b6 (11... Qa5 $5) 12. Bh6 Re8 13. f4 Bb7 14. Ne3 Nc5 $13 {0-1 (28) Fercec,N (2466) -Cvitan,O (2528)/Zagreb 2012}) 11. f3 Bxc3 {Black must not miss the opportunity.} 12. bxc3 Be6 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4,Gc5]} 13. Bh6 Re8 14. Ne3 Rc8 15. f4 (15. Nd5 f6 16. Be3 Ne5 $13) 15... f6 {The game is complex, open for all three outcomes.} 16. Bg4 $6 (16. Qe1 Qa5) 16... Bxg4 17. Nxg4 Kh8 18. Qe2 Qd7 19. e5 (19. f5 Ne5 20. Nxe5 dxe5 $17) 19... f5 $17 {0-1 (32) Biriukov,N (2325) -Zubarev,A (2536)/Alushta 2010}) (10. Nd5 Nc5 11. f3 f5 12. exf5 Bxf5) 10... a5 {White has many options now.} 11. Na3 {[%cal Ba3b5]} (11. Rb1 Nc5 12. f3 f5 $1 {Excellent break, played with good timing. Black takes advantage of the bad location of the rook on b1. Harmless is} 13. Be3 (13. exf5 $2 Bxf5 {[%csl Rb1][%cal Gf5b1]} 14. g4 {There are no alternatives that work.} (14. Nd5 $2 Nd4 $19 15. Nxd4 Bxd4+ 16. Kh1 Bxb1 17. Qxb1 e6 $19 {1/2-1/2 Bromberger,S  (2407)-Grafl,F (2341)/Augsburg 2002}) (14. Rc1 $2 Nd3 15. Bxd3 Bxd3 16. Re1 Bxc4 $17) 14... Bxc2 15. Qxc2 Qd7 $15) 13... fxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. fxe4 Rxf1+ {[%csl Be4,Bc4]} 16. Bxf1 Be6 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 19. Qxd4 Qc7 20. Bd3 Qc5 $15 {Â1/ 2-Â1/ 2 (23) Lenic,L (2584)-Sebenik,M (2485)/Ljubljana 2008}) (11. Rc1 {has been played:} Nc5 12. b3 (12. f3 Nb4 13. b3 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Nxa2) 12... Nb4 $1 {As in the game Pelletier, Y-Bologan,V Aix les Bains 2011, this knight manoeuvre is very effective.} 13. Rb1 (13. a3 $2 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Na2 $19) 13... Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Nxe4 15. Bb2 Nxc2 (15... Nc5 $5 16. Ra1 e5 $15) 16. Qxc2 Nc5 {White has compensation for the pawn, but we find the black position preferable.} 17. Rbd1 b6 18. f4 Bf5 19. Qc3 f6 20. Qe3 $44 {1/2-1/2 Nunn,J (2600)-Petursson,M (2555)/ Wijk aan Zee 1990}) 11... Nc5 12. Nab5 Nd4 $5 {The idea of this move is to simplify and take the game towards better known paths.} 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. Bh6 Bg7 {Trying to reach typical Maroczy positions.} (14... Bxc3 $5 15. bxc3 (15. Bxf8 $2 Bxb2 16. Rb1 Bf6 17. Bh6 Nxe4 $17) 15... Re8 16. Qd4 e5 17. Qe3 Bd7 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd7c6]} (17... Qh4 $5 18. f3 Ne6 {[%cal Gg6g5]}) 18. f4 Bc6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc6e4,Gc5e4,Gd8h4]} 19. f5 Qh4 (19... Nxe4 $1 $15) 20. Bf3 Nxe4 21. g3 Qh3 $13 {1-0 Tate,A (2334)-Lie,K (2560)/Porto Carras 2011}) 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qd4+ $5 (16. f4 e5 {A risky move that seeks to consolidate on the dark squares. The drawback is that the second player is not as well-developed as in the variation 14...Bxc3, and d6 is an exploitable weakness.} (16... f6 17. Qd2 Bd7) 17. f5 f6 (17... Qb6 18. Kh1 f6 19. Rf3 $16) 18. Kh1 b6 19. Qd2 Bb7 20. Bf3 (20. Qe3 $1 $16) 20... Qe7 21. Rad1 Rad8 $13 {[%cal Gb7c6,Ge7b7] 0-1 (34) Ostos,J (2335) -Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2470)/San Felipe 2008}) (16. Bg4 $1 Bxg4 17. Qxg4 a4 18. Qe2 Qa5 19. Rac1 Nd7 20. Nd5 Nf6 $1 21. Rfd1 $1 (21. Nxf6 exf6 $1 {[%csl Re4,Gf5][%cal Gf8e8,Ge8e4,Gf6f5] Black gets dynamic compensation for his deteriorated structure.} 22. Rfd1 Qb6 23. Rd5 Ra5 24. Rcd1 Rxd5 25. Rxd5 Re8 $13 {[%cal Gf6f5]}) 21... Nxd5 22. Rxd5 $1 (22. exd5 Rfe8 23. h4 e6 24. b3 Qd8 25. h5 axb3 26. axb3 Qg5 $13) 22... Qa6 (22... Qb6 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gb6c5,Gf8c8,Gc8c5]}) 23. h4 Rfc8 $14 {1-0 (41) Bologan,V (2663)-Motylev,A (2634)/ Togliatti 2003}) (16. Qd2 {An interesting attempt with the idea to avoid Black's immediate e5. It has been played in master tournaments.} Bd7 (16... e5 $2 17. Rad1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd2d6]} Be6 (17... Ra6 18. f4 exf4 19. Qxf4 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) 18. Qxd6 $18) 17. Rfe1 Bc6 18. Bf1 a4 $1 (18... e5 $2 19. Rad1 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) 19. Rad1 f6 20. f4 Qa5 {White has different alternatives.} 21. Re3 (21. e5 $2 dxe5 22. fxe5 f5 $15) (21. Qe3 $5 Rad8 22. Nd5 (22. e5 $2 {was counterproductive for White:} dxe5 23. fxe5 f5 24. e6 Ne4 $17 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ga5c5,Gc5e5]}) (22. Rd2 Nxe4 $17) (22. f5 Nd7 $13 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5][%cal Ga5c5,Gd7e5]}) 22... e6 23. Nc3 Qb4 $13 {Both sides have equal chances.}) 21... Rad8 22. Kh1 e5 23. f5 g5 (23... gxf5 24. exf5 Kh8 $13 {The position is one of dynamic equality.}) 24. Qe2 Rh8 25. Rh3 h5 26. Re3 (26. Rxh5 a3 $1) 26... h4 $14 {1-0 (34) Charbonneau,P (2499) -Kudrin,S (2563)/ICC INT 2008}) 16... e5 $5 (16... Kg8 17. f4 $16 {This is comfortable for White.}) 17. Qd2 Ne6 $1 $146 {Our improvement for the second player.} (17... Be6 $2 18. Rad1 Qb6 (18... Ra6 19. f4 $16) 19. Qxd6 $18) (17... Ra6 $2 {has been played:} 18. Rad1 Bd7 (18... Be6 19. f4 $16) 19. Kh1 Re8 (19... f5 20. exf5 Bxf5 21. f4 $16) 20. f4 $16 {Barrientos, Sergio (2417)- Alonso, Salvador (2403), Peru 2007}) 18. Rfd1 {As there are no games with this move, we analyse different possible variations.} (18. Bg4 Nf4 19. Bf3 (19. Bxc8 $4 Qg5 $1 $19)) (18. Nb5 $6 Qf6 19. Nxd6 (19. Qxd6 Rd8 20. Qb6 Qg5 $40 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gd8d2,Ge6f4,Ge6d4,Gg5g2,Gd8d3,Gd3f3]}) (19. g3 Bd7 20. Nxd6 Nd4 $19 {[%csl Gd4]} 21. Nb5 Bh3 22. Rfd1 Nf3+ $19) 19... Rd8 $15) (18. Rac1 $5 Nd4 19. Nb5 Nxb5 20. cxb5 Be6 21. Bc4 Qe7 22. Bxe6 Qxe6 {[%cal Ge6a2]} 23. b3 a4 $1 $13 {This break evens the game.} 24. Rc7 axb3 25. axb3 Qxb3 26. Rxb7 Rab8) 18... Nd4 19. Nb5 $1 (19. b3 Bd7 $1 (19... Be6 $1 20. Nb5 Nxb5 21. cxb5 a4 $13) 20. Bf1 {Preparing the expulsion of the black knight.} Bc6 21. Ne2 (21. f3 f5 $1 $132 22. Ne2 $2 (22. Bd3 Qh4 $13) 22... Nxe2+ 23. Qxe2 fxe4 24. fxe4 Qb6+ 25. Kh1 Rf4 $19) 21... Ne6 22. f3 Qb6+ 23. Kh1 Rfd8) 19... Nxb5 20. cxb5 Be6 $1 21. a4 (21. Qxd6 Qxd6 22. Rxd6 Rfd8 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 $44) 21... Qb6 $1 {[%csl Gd8][%cal Gf8d8,Gd6d5]} 22. Qxd6 Qxd6 23. Rxd6 Rfd8 $1 {Despite the missing pawn, Black has no problems in the endgame.} 24. Rad1 (24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Rd1 Rc8 {[%csl Ra4,Rb2][%cal Ge6b3,Gc8c2,Gc2b2,Gb3a4]}) 24... Rxd6 25. Rxd6 Rc8 $1 26. f3 (26. h4 $2 Rc1+ 27. Kh2 Rc2 $19) (26. Rd2 $2 Rc1+ 27. Rd1 Rc2 $19) (26. Bd1 Rc1 27. Kf1 Rb1) 26... Rc2 27. Bf1 (27. Bd1 $2 Rxb2 28. Rb6 $19) 27... Rxb2 28. Rb6 Bc8 $5 (28... Rb4 29. Rxb7 Rxa4) 29. Bc4 Rb4 30. Bd5 {The 6.Nc2 scheme has some peculiarities of its own within the Marozcy. It shouldn't be underestimated, but we think Black can get a good game with precise play.} *

