1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 {An interesting secondary alternative that can be valuable to incorporate into the repertoire.} (6... Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6 {This is a transposition to 6.... d6;.} 8. Bg5 $5 {In this line, White has this interesting development option. The bishop on g5 puts pressure on the sensitive pawn on e7. This should not be worrying for Black, though, as he can continue with his ideas. At the same time, the piece on g5 can provide extra tactical themes in favour of the second player.} Bg7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. Be2 a5 $1 {[%cal Ba5a4] This is the idea that we suggest, to continue with the typical plans of the Be3 variation.} 11. O-O (11. Qe3) 11... a4 $1 {As in the Be3 variation, Black gains space on the queenside.} 12. Qe3 (12. Rac1 Qa5 13. Rfd1 Be6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ge6c4,Gf8c8]} 14. f3 (14. Nd5 $2 Nxe4 $1 15. Qxa5 Rxa5 16. Bxe7 (16. Nxe7+ Kh8 {[%cal Bg7b2]} 17. Be3 Bxb2 18. Rc2 Bf6 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. cxd5 $19) 16... Re8 17. Bh4 Bxb2 $19) 14... Rfc8 15. Nb5 Qxd2 16. Rxd2 Kf8 {Black already has a very comfortable position.} 17. Be3 Nd7 18. Kf2 Nc5 {And the second player ended up winning. 0-1 (23) Duncan,C (2245)-Melkumyan,H (2633)/London ENG 2016}) (12. Rab1 {[%cal Gb2b4] With the idea of supporting the advance of the b-pawn.} Qa5 13. b4 axb3 14. axb3 Qb4 {Not allowing b4.} 15. Rfc1 Ra3 16. Qd1 (16. Nd5 $2 Qxd2 17. Nxe7+ Kh8 18. Bxd2 Ra2 $19) 16... Be6 $13) 12... Qa5 13. Rac1 Be6 14. f4 {This aggressive play by White is easily countered.} Rfc8 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ge6c4,Gc8c4]} 15. b3 axb3 16. axb3 Qc5 $1 17. Qxc5 Rxc5 {[%cal Ba8a3]} 18. Bf3 Ra3 19. Rb1 h6 20. Bh4 Bxc4 21. bxc4 Rxc3 $13 {0-1 Vidit,S (2689)-Melkumyan,H (2633)/ Doha QAT 2016}) 7. Be2 (7. Be3 {is not possible due to} Ng4 $1) 7... Nxd4 {This is the idea behind 6... d6;.} (7... Bg7 8. Be3 {, we reach the mainline.}) 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 (9. Bg5 {The other option, transposing to 6. ..Nxd4.}) 9... O-O 10. Qd2 a5 11. Rd1 (11. O-O a4 $1 {Gaining space. Now White has two moves to choose from.} 12. Bd4 {This does not cause Black any discomfort.} (12. Rac1 Qa5 13. f3 Bd7 (13... Be6 $5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf8c8,Gc8c4,Ge6c4]} 14. Nd5 Qxd2 15. Nxe7+ Kh8 16. Bxd2 Rfe8 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. cxd5 Bxd5 {Practice has shown that Black has no problems.}) 14. c5 {The only way to play ambitiously.} (14. Rfd1 Bc6 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gf6d7]}) 14... Bc6 (14... dxc5 $4 15. e5 $18) 15. cxd6 Rfd8 {With this move, Black achieves the typical active countergame of this opening.} 16. Bc4 (16. Nb1 {Too passive.} Qxd2 17. Nxd2 exd6 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 18. Nc4 d5 19. Nb6 Rab8 20. Bf4 dxe4 21. Bxb8) (16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Bxd5 19. dxe7 Re8 20. Bc5 Bc6 {[%csl Rb2,Re7][%cal Gg7b2,Gg7f6,Gf6e7] White's pawn on the seventh rank can be a strenght or a weakness. Black has dynamic balance.}) 16... Rxd6 17. Qf2 Nd7 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3][%cal Gg7c3,Ga4a3] Black suffered no damage to his pawn structure and has more piece activity.} 18. Rfd1 (18. a3 b5 $1 $36) 18... a3 19. Rxd6 exd6 20. b4 $2 (20. Bf1 $15) 20... Qxb4 $17 21. Nd5 Qb2 22. Rc2 Qb1+ (22... Bxd5 $1 23. Bxd5 Bd4 $3 $19) 23. Rc1 Qb2 24. Rc2 {1/2-1/2 Duda,J (2707)-Ivanchuk,V (2728)/ Tbilisi GEO 2017}) (12. f3 Qa5 13. Rac1 Be6 14. Nd5 Qxd2 15. Nxe7+ Kh8 16. Bxd2 Rfe8 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. cxd5 Bxd5 19. Bb5 Re5 20. Bc3 Bxa2 21. Bxe5 Bxe5) 12... Bd7 13. Qe3 Bc6 (13... Qa5 $5) 14. Nd5 Bxd5 {After this capture, Black remains somewhat passive, but should be able to hold his position easily.} (14... Nd7 $5 {leads to the kind of position we want:} 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Rfd1 e5 17. Nc3 Nc5 18. Rd2 Qe7) 15. exd5 Nd7 $1 16. Rfd1 (16. b4 $5 {should be played, aiming for c5 as quickly as possible.}) 16... Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Qb6 18. Qxb6 Nxb6 {The endgame is equal, although the first player has to play carefully.} 19. f4 Rfc8 (19... f5 20. Kf2 Rfc8 21. Rdc1 Kf7 {1/2-1/2 Yu Yangyi (2738)-Duda,J (2758)/Moscow RUS 2019 (38)}) 20. b3 axb3 21. axb3 Nd7 22. b4 Rxa1 23. Rxa1 Nb6 {[%cal Gb6d5,Gb6c4]} 24. Ra7 Rc7 $15) 11... a4 {[%cal Gd8a5,Gc8d7,Gd7c6,Gf6d7] This pawn advance allows to gain space for Black's pieces.} (11... Be6 $5 12. b3 {This routine move is too tame and allows Black to carry out his plan.} (12. f4 $5 $146 {, trying to punish the bishop's development to e6.}) 12... a4 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4] Taking advantage of the defenselessness of the white pawn on e4 as well as gaining space and providing good play for Black's pieces.} 13. O-O axb3 14. axb3 Nd7 (14... Qa5 $5 {may be a more exact order, avoiding a future white b4.}) 15. Nb5 (15. b4 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5]}) 15... Nc5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc5e4]} 16. Qc2 Qa5 17. Bd4 Qa2 18. Qc3 Bxd4 19. Nxd4 Bd7 20. Qe3 e5 $1 {Taking control of the dark squares.} 21. Nf3 (21. Nf5 $1 {The best practical chance.}) 21... Bg4 $1 {Eliminating the piece that defends the dark squares.} 22. Rxd6 Bxf3 23. Bxf3 Nxb3 24. Rb6 Nd4 $17 25. Rxb7 Ra3 26. Qh6 Qxc4 27. Rc1 Qa6 28. Rbb1 Nxf3+ 29. gxf3 Rxf3 30. Re1 Qf6 {0-1 Almasi,Z (2682)-Kuzubov,Y (2699)/Riyadh KSA 2017}) 12. c5 {The logical attempt to punish the last black move.} Be6 13. cxd6 Qxd6 14. Qxd6 exd6 15. a3 {We are in a similar position to the line with h3 (Chapter 06). Black has adequate counterplay to compensate for his weak pawn on d6.} (15. Rxd6 $2 a3 $1 $17 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3,Re4][%cal Gf8c8,Ga8a3,Gg7c3]}) 15... Rfc8 (15... Rfd8 16. Bb6 (16. f3 $6 {A dubious central consolidation move.} Bb3 17. Rd2 $6 (17. Bb6 {should be played, looking for equality.}) 17... d5 $1 $15 {A perfect moment for this advance. Black is better.} 18. e5 Nh5 19. g4 $2 (19. Bd1 Bxe5 20. Bxb3 Bxc3 21. bxc3 axb3 22. Bc5 Nf4 $15 {And it is White who fights for equality.}) 19... Bxe5 20. gxh5 d4 $1 $17 {1/2-1/2 Mareco,S (2634)-Felgaer,R (2560)/Buenos Aires ARG 2019 (43)}) 16... Rd7 17. O-O (17. Bb5 Bb3 $1 $132 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd7e7,Ge7e4]}) 17... Bb3 18. Rd2 Re7 19. f3 (19. Bf3 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gg7c3,Gd7e5,Ge5c4]}) 19... d5 $1 {Again, this blow guarantees good play for the second player.} 20. Bc5 (20. Nxd5 Nxd5 21. exd5 Bxd5) 20... Re6 (20... Rc7 $5) 21. exd5 Nxd5 22. Nxd5 Bxd5 23. Bb5 Bb3 $15 {0-1 (24) Szelag,M (2466)-Kanarek,M (2519)/Poland POL 2017 (56)}) 16. Bd4 (16. Rxd6 Rxc3 $5 (16... Nd7 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3][%cal Gd7c5,Gc5b3,Gg7c3,Gc5e4]}) 17. bxc3 Nxe4 18. Rb6 $13) (16. O-O b5 (16... Rxc3) 17. Bxb5 Rab8 $1 $132 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3,Re4][%cal Gb8b2,Gf6e4] The stupendous piece activity offers smooth play for Black.}) 16... Bb3 17. Ra1 d5 $1 $36 18. e5 Nd7 19. f4 f6 (19... Nc5 $1 {was more precise:} 20. Nb5 Ne6 21. Bg4 Rc4 22. Bxe6 fxe6 23. Be3 Bf8 24. Nd6 Bxd6 25. exd6 Rd8 26. Rc1 Rxc1+ 27. Bxc1 Rxd6 $17) 20. exf6 Bxf6 21. Bxf6 Nxf6 22. O-O d4 23. Nb5 Rc2 $2 (23... Re8 $17 {[%cal Ga8d8,Ge8e3]} 24. Bd3 (24. Nxd4 $2 Rad8 $19) (24. Bf3 Rad8 $19) (24. Nc7 Rxe2 25. Nxa8 d3 $19) 24... Re3 25. Rf3 Rxd3 26. Rxd3 Bc4 $17) 24. Rf2 $2 (24. Nxd4 Rd2 25. Nxb3) 24... Rd8 25. Bd3 Rc5 26. Re2 Bc4 27. Bxc4+ Rxc4 28. Rd1 d3 29. Nc3 Rxf4 30. Rf2 Rxf2 31. Kxf2 Ng4+ 32. Kf3 h5 33. h3 Rf8+ 34. Kg3 Ne5 35. Nxa4 h4+ 36. Kxh4 (36. Kh2 Rc8 37. Nc3 Kf7 $17) 36... Rf4+ 37. Kg3 Rxa4 $19 {0-1 Pantsulaia,L (2612)-Guseinov, G (2646)/Riyadh KSA 2017 (51)} *

