1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. e4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Bd7 10. h3 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. Qc2 {White's setup looks strange at first, but if you take a closer look, you realize that it is not easy to find a good move for Black. White threatens to play b4 or simply Rd1, followed by e5 and c5.} a5 (12... Nd7 {I had this move twice in my practice and won both games pretty confidently.} 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. b4 $1 $14 {1-0 Arnaudov,P (2459)-Jakubiec,A (2508) Bundesliga 1819 Germany 2018 (4.5) The threat is simply b4-b5. White is better.}) 13. Rad1 Nd7 $6 {In my opinion this move, Black is in trouble after this move.} (13... a4 {I believe that this is Black's best chance, but we will discuss this move in the other game.}) 14. Bxg7 $1 Kxg7 15. Bg4 $1 Ne5 {This is the main try for Black, but it also isn't enough to solve the problems.} ({Against} 15... Nf6 {Andreikin,D (2737) -Mamedov,R (2688) EU-ch blitz Tallinn 2016 (13) ½-½} 16. c5 {follows the same.}) (15... Rc8 {After this move, Black is almost lost} 16. a4 Rc7 17. Bxd7 Rxd7 18. b3 $18 {Whites knight is much stronger than Black's bishop}) 16. c5 Nxg4 17. hxg4 Bd7 {Black tries to solve his problems tactically.} (17... Rc8 18. cxd6 exd6 19. Qd2 $16) (17... Qc8 {This is Black's main try, but I believe White can simply force an almost winning position with only major pieces on the board.} 18. cxd6 Qxg4 19. dxe7 Rfe8 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. Qc3+ Kg8 22. exd5 Rxe7 23. d6 {1-0 Cheparinov,I (2711)-Amin,B (2709) Zagreb Peace 2018 (6) Now White simply puts the rook on d5 and starts pushing f-pawn. Combining an attack against the king with the strength of the d6-pawn.}) 18. cxd6 Bxg4 19. dxe7 Qxe7 20. Nd5 $1 {but White's position is simply too powerful} Qe5 21. f3 Rac8 22. Qf2 Be6 23. f4 $1 Qxe4 24. Rfe1 Qc2 25. Qd4+ Kh6 26. g4 $6 {[%cal Yd1d2,Yd2h2,Gg4g5]} (26. Ne3 Qc5 27. Qf6 $18 {[%cal Yg1f2,Ge1h1]}) 26... Qc5 $2 (26... Rfd8 $1 27. g5+ (27. Rd3 Bxg4) (27. Rd2 $2 Rxd5 $1) 27... Kh5 28. Qe3 Kh4 $3 {amazingly Blacks king can survive here.}) 27. g5+ Kh5 28. Nf6+ Kh4 29. Qxc5 Rxc5 30. Kf2 $18 Rc2+ 31. Kf3 Rh2 32. Rh1 Rh3+ 33. Rxh3+ Bxh3 34. Rh1 Rd8 35. Ne4 {[%cal Ye4f2]} Rd3+ 36. Ke2 Rd4 37. Ke3 1-0

