1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 b6 {this is an interesting system} 9. O-O {Black is keeping the pawn on d7 and wants to break with d5 at an appropriate moment.} Bb7 10. Ndb5 {I like this move a lot. White is trying to provoke a7-a6 when the b6-pawn is weak.} (10. f3 {leads to a very sharp play} e6 11. Qd2 d5 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. cxd5 exd5 14. e5 Ne8 15. f4 f6 {White is probably slightly better, but I think that Black has enough counterplay.}) 10... Qb8 (10... a6 11. Na3 d6 12. Qd2 Nd7 {[%cal Rf1d1,Ra1c1]} 13. Rfd1 $16) 11. f3 Rd8 12. Qd2 d6 13. Nd5 Rd7 14. Bh6 $16 {Black is without counterplay} Bh8 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. f4 {[%cal Re4e5]} a6 $2 17. e5 $3 {Black missed this strong reply} Bg7 (17... axb5 18. exf6 bxc4 19. Bg4 e6 20. Rae1 $18) 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. e6 $3 {The point of White's idea} Rd8 (19... fxe6 20. Nd4 Nxd4 21. Qxd4+ Kf7 22. Bg4 $18 {[%cal Ra1e1]}) 20. exf7 Rf8 21. Nd4 Rxf7 22. Ne6+ Kg8 23. Bf3 (23. f5 {was faster, but White doesn't want to allow Ne5}) 23... Na5 24. Bd5 Qc8 25. Rac1 {and Black simply resigns in this hopeless position.} 1-0

